  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Standards and Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Shared global standards for preventing financial crimes\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing agreements\n- Extradition protocols\n- Joint investigative efforts\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border financial monitoring\n- Uniform anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n\n4. Enforcement Coordination\n- International prosecution strategies\n- Shared intelligence networks\n- Coordinated financial investigations\n- Sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n\n5. Treaty Obligations\n- Binding international agreements\n- Requirement for national legislation alignment\n- Consistent legal definitions\n- Standardized investigative procedures\n\n6. Financial Institution Oversight\n- Global banking regulations\n- Transnational corporate compliance standards\n- International banking transparency requirements\n\nEach jurisdiction implements these frameworks differently, but the overall goal is creating a comprehensive global approach to preventing financial crimes.",
